\par }\pard\plain \nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \cgrid {\lang2057 
\par Actor is a program designed to analyse sentences the user types in, store the words and some contextual information about these words, and generate some reply sentence to output to the user.  It's based on an old program called Niall (Non-Intelligent Amos
 
Language Learner) which was written in AMOS (natch) by some guy named (I think) Matthew Peck.  It was released on an Amiga Format cover disk many, many years ago.  In turn that was based on an even older program, so I don't really feel I'm ripping anybody
 off :).
\par 
\par Here's a quick illustration.  Say you start with a new actor and type in as an input sentence.
\par 
\par \tab Greetings to one and all.
\par 
\par Now the program analyses that sentences and stores the connections between the words.  For instance, 'to' is stored as a wo
rd with two links - a previous one to the word 'Greetings' and a next link to the word 'one'.  In the same way, the word 'all' is stored with a previous link to the word 'and' and a next link to an 'end-of-sentence' control word.
\par 
\par Since the program only knows this set of words initially, the first response will always be to dumbly echo your input back to you.  In other words, the actor will say
\par 
\par \tab Greetings to one and all.
\par 
\par However, say the next sentence you typed was,
\par 
\par \tab Have you got one in the oven?
\par 
\par The actor conducts the same analysis as previously.  But now the actor has two sets of words in its vocabulary, including the word 'one' which has occured twice.  Thus, in it's reply, the actor could use this to construct a sentence such as
\par 
\par \tab Greetings to one in the oven.
\par 
\par Hilarity ensues (or not, but you get the general idea :).  More often that not the actor will reply with some complete garbage but hey, that's what you get for randomly sticking bits of sentences together.  I'm trying to think of ways to cut do
wn on this and if you have any suggestions, I'd be interested in hearing about them.
\par 
\par Layered on this basic structure is an attempt to implement contextual links, which you can read about in the next section.
\par }\pard\plain \s1\sb240\sa60\keepn\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright \b\fs36\kerning28\cgrid {\lang2057 \page }{\cs16\lang2057\super #{\footnote \pard\plain \s15\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {\cs16\super #}{ Contextualisation
}}${\footnote \pard\plain \s15\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {\cs16\super $}{ Contextualisation}}}{\lang2057 Contextualisation
\par }\pard\plain \nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \cgrid {\lang2057 
\par This version attempts to implement contextual links in a primitive way.  This is done by storing the words above a certain length that the actor replies with and li
nking them to the words also above that length which the user replies with.  Once these links are stored, the actor looks out for the words in user input sentences and if it sees them, will choose to build reply sentences out of words contextual linked to
 the user's words.
\par 
\par To illustrate this, suppose the actor said something like,
\par 
\par \tab I hear buffalo make good meat.
\par 
\par and the user replied with
\par 
\par \tab So what.  I'm a vegetarian.
\par 
\par Supposing the contextual word threshold is six letters.  Then 'buffalo' in the actor's sentence will be linked with the word 'vegetarian'.  If a few sentences later the user says something such as
\par \tab 
\par \tab I think it's barbaric to eat buffalo.
\par 
\par The actor will see that the word buffalo is a contextual link and may well reply with a sentence incorporating the linked word 'vegetarian', such as
\par 
\par \tab Vegetarian meals are very nice.
\par 
\par This is not, as you can appreciate, anywhere near perfect and is another aspect of the program to improve.  This version attempts to do that by introducing the concept of contextual exclusion, as discussed in the next section.
\par }\pard\plain \s1\sb240\sa60\keepn\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright \b\fs36\kerning28\cgrid {\lang2057 \page }{\cs16\lang2057\super #{\footnote \pard\plain \s15\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {\cs16\super #}{ Exclusion}}$
