Contextual Exclusion
\par }\pard\plain \nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \cgrid {
\par Deciding what words are contextual or not by how long they are is a crude way of doing it.  In an attempt to refine this, you can now specify words which are to be ignored in contextualisation, even if they meet the word limit.
\par 
\par For instance, take the sentence
\par 
\par }{\lang2057 \tab I think it's barbaric to eat buffalo.
\par 
\par Supposing the contextual word limit is 6 letters, both \lquote barbaric\rquote  and \lquote buffalo\rquote  will be picked out as contextual words.  However, you may regard the word \lquote barbaric\rquote  as a general verb which shouldn\rquote 
t be used to link sentences together.  To stop this, \lquote barbaric\rquote  can be specified in the file }{\b\lang2057 exclude\\exclude.txt}{\lang2057 , which currently must be 
